CustomTDMTasks

getTasksByParamsGet

The API filters the returned tasks based on the input filtering parameters. It invokes either regularTasksByUser API to bring regular tasks or VersionTasksByUser API to bring data versioning (Data Flux) tasks. The selection of the API that is used to get the tasks for the user is based on the value of the version_ind input value: - If the version_ind is true (get data versioning tasks): call the /VersionTasksByUser API. - If the version_ind is false or empty: call the /regularTasksByUser API. The filteringParam input is a dynamic JSON string. It is an optional parameter. If is it not populated, the API returns all of the user's regular tasks. The following filtering parameters are supported: - task_type: - Populate the task type to filter the returned tasks based on their type. - Valid values: - LOAD - EXTRACT - RESERVE - Notes: - To get a reserve-only task, populate the task type with RESERVE. - To get a delete-only task, populate the task type with LOAD, load_entity with false, and delete_before_load with true. - version_ind: - Populate with false to get regular tasks. - Populate with true to get data versioning tasks. - load_entity: - Populate with true to get tasks that load (provision) data to the target environment. - For other tasks (extract, reserve only, and delete only), populate this field with false. - delete_before_load: - Populate with true to get delete only or load&delete tasks. - Else, populate this parameter with false. - selection_method: The entity?s selection method: - 'L' (Entity list) - 'P' or 'PR' (Parameters) - 'CLONE' (Entity Clone) - 'GEN' (Generate Synthetic) - 'R' (Random) - 'C' (Custom Logic) - 'ALL' (Extract tasks: select a predefined entity list. Load Data Versioning tasks: select all entities of the selected version) - 'REF' (Reference Only) - sync_mode: - Populate this parameter to get tasks that override the default sync mode (sync ON which syncs new data based on the LU?s implementation sync policy): - OFF - FORCE API Input Examples: ================== {"task_type":"EXTRACT", "version_ind":false, "selection_method":"L", "sync_mode":"FORCE"} {"task_type":"LOAD", "version_ind":false, "load_entity":false, "delete_before_load":true, "selection_method":"L"} Get all data versioning (Data Flux) load tasks for the user: {"task_type":"LOAD", "version_ind":true}

Responses

Status: 200 - OK

  • Schema

regularTasksByUserGet

Gets the list of regular active tasks (version_ind is 'false', task_status and task_execution_status columns are 'Active') for a user based on the user's permission group (admin, owner, or tester) and based on the user's TDM environment permissions: Admin Users: =========== - Get all active regular tasks. Tester Users: =========== Extract Tasks: - Get all active tasks that do not require special permissions (that is, tasks that do not include reference tables, do not require up-to-date data, or that do not run on all entities) if the user or their group has a Read TDM Environment permission set on at least one TDM environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. - Get all active tasks that include reference tables or that require up-to-date data if the user or their group has a Read TDM Environment permission set with these permissions on at least one TDM environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. Load Tasks: - Get all active tasks that do not require special permissions (that is, tasks that do not include reference tables, do not include Cloning or Random selection methods, tasks that do not have Sequence replacement, or tasks that do not include a delete of entities from the target system) if the user or their group has a Read TDM Environment permission set on at least one TDM environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs, and a Write TDM Environment permission set on at least one TDM environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. - Get all active tasks that require special permissions if the user or their group has at least one Read TDM Environment permission set, and one Write TDM Environment permission set with these permissions and the source and target environments have the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. Delete Tasks: - Get all active delete tasks if the user has at least one Write TDM Environment permission set with a permission to delete entities and the environment has the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. Reserve Tasks: - Get all active reserve tasks if the the user has at least one Write TDM Environment permission set and the Max Number of Reserved Entities on Env setting is bigger than zero and the environment has the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. Owner Users: =========== Extract Tasks: - Get all active tasks if the user or their group is the owner of at least one source environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. - Get active tasks based on the tester's selection logic, since an owner can also be attached to the TDM environment as a tester. Load Tasks: - Get all active tasks if the user or their group is the owner of at least one source environment and one target environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. - Get active tasks based on the tester's selection logic, since an owner can also be attached to the TDM environment as a tester. Delete Tasks: - Get all active tasks if the user or their group is the owner of at least one target environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. - Get all active delete tasks if the user has at least one Write TDM Environment permission set with a permission to delete entities and the environment has the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. Reserve Tasks: - Get all active tasks if the user or their group is the owner of at least one target environment with the task's Business Entity (BE) and LUs. - Get all active reserve tasks if the the user has at least one Write TDM Environment permission set and the Max Number of Reserved Entities on Env setting is bigger than zero.

  • Schema

versionTasksByUserGet

Gets data versioning (Data Flux) tasks with version_ind set to true. Only active tasks (task_status and task_execution_status columns are 'Active') are taken, The task list is returned for the user based on the user's permission group (admin, owner, or tester) and based on the user's TDM environment permissions: Admin Users: - Get all active tasks. Owner Users: - Get all active extract tasks if the user is the owner of at least one source environment. - Get all active load tasks if the user is the owner of at least one source environment and one target environment. - Get all active extract tasks if the user has at least one Read TDM Environment permission set that enables a data versioning. - Get all active load tasks if the user has at least one Read TDM Environment permission set and one Write TDM Environment permission set that enable a data versioning. Tester Users: - Get all active extract tasks if the user has at least one Read TDM Environment permission set that enables a data versioning. - Get all active load tasks if the user has at least one Read TDM Environment permission set and one Write TDM Environment permission set that enable a data versioning.

import io.swagger.client.*;
import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.LuApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class LuApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();


        LuApi apiInstance = new LuApi();
        String luName = luName_example; // String | 
        Boolean zip = true; // Boolean | download logical unit project files
        try {
            map['String', Object] result = apiInstance.luLuNameGet(luName, zip);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling LuApi#luLuNameGet");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

businessentityBeIdLogicalunitLuIdPut

Updates an LU in a Business Entity: updates the description, parent LU or the DC name LU's settings. Note that if the Logical Unit it not attached to any product, the product_id must be populated by -1 and the product_name is null. Example request body: { "logicalUnit": { "lu_description": null, "be_id": 1, "lu_parent_id": null, "lu_parent_name": null, "product_id": -1, "lu_dc_name": null, "product_name": null, "lu_id": 24, } }


/businessentity/{beId}/logicalunit/{luId}

businessentityBeIdLogicalunitsPut

Updates the Business Entity's Logical Units. Example request body: { "product_id": 1, "product_name": "PROD", "logicalUnits": [ { "lu_description": "updatedDescription", "be_id": 1, "lu_parent_id": null, "lu_parent_name": null, "lu_dc_name": "updatedDcName", "lu_id": 24, },{ "lu_description": "updatedDescription", "be_id": 1, "lu_parent_id": 26, "lu_parent_name": "parentLuName", "lu_dc_name": "updatedDcName", "lu_id": 23, } ] }


/businessentity/{beId}/logicalunits

environmentEnvIdEnvnameEnvNameRoleRoleIdRolenameRoleNameUsersPost

Updates the Testers setting on an TDM Environment permission set (role): add or delete testers. Note that this API needs to get the update testers list in the input BODY. Example of a request body: { "users": [ { "user_id ": "-1", "username": "ALL" }, { "user_id": "tester1", "username": "tester1" } ] }


/environment/{envId}/envname/{envName}/role/{roleId}/rolename/{roleName}/users

environmentEnvIdPut

Modifies Environment's general properties. The following parameters are mandatory: emvId, environment_name, allow_write, and allow_read. Notes: > Both parameters - environment_name amd fabric environment_name - are populated by one of the Fabric's environments. > The sync_mode parameter can be populated by one of the following values: "OFF", "FORCE" or null. > The allow_write parameter is set to true if the environment can be used as a target environment. Else, set this parameter to false. > The allow_read parameter is set to true if the environment can be used as a source environment. Else, set this parameter to false. Example of the owners: "owners":[{"uid":"king123","user_id":"king123","displayName":"king123","username":"king123"},{"uid":"owner1","user_id":"owner1","displayName":"owner1","username":"owner1"}]


/environment/{envId}

use Data::Dumper;

use WWW::SwaggerClient::TDMEnvironmentsApi;


my $api_instance = WWW::SwaggerClient::TDMEnvironmentsApi->new();
my $envId = 1.2; # BigDecimal | Environment name. The environment name must also be defined in Fabric's environments.
my $body = WWW::SwaggerClient::Object::Environment_envId_body->new(); # Environment_envId_body | 

eval { 
    my $result = $api_instance->environmentEnvIdPut(envId => $envId, body => $body);
    print Dumper($result);
};
if ($@) {
    warn "Exception when calling TDMEnvironmentsApi->environmentEnvIdPut: $@\n";
}

body =  # Environment_envId_body |  (optional)

    api_response = api_instance.environment_env_id_put(envId, body=body)
    pprint(api_response)
except ApiException as e:
    print("Exception when calling TDMEnvironmentsApi->environmentEnvIdPut: %s\n" % e)

environmentEnvIdRoleRoleIdUsersGet

Gets the list of users attached to a given TDM Environment permission set (role).


/environment/{envId}/role/{roleId}/users

import io.swagger.client.*;
import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.TDMEnvironmentsApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class TDMEnvironmentsApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();


        TDMEnvironmentsApi apiInstance = new TDMEnvironmentsApi();
        BigDecimal envId = 1.2; // BigDecimal | 
        BigDecimal roleId = 1.2; // BigDecimal | 
        try {
            Object result = apiInstance.environmentEnvIdRoleRoleIdUsersGet(envId, roleId);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling TDMEnvironmentsApi#environmentEnvIdRoleRoleIdUsersGet");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

environmentEnvIdRolesGet

Gets all TDM Environment permission sets (roles) of a given environment.


/environment/{envId}/roles

environmentEnvIdSummaryIntervalGet

Gets a summary information and statistics on the tasks executed over the last month on a given environment: > Processed Entities, the number of entities processed by tasks executed on the environment. > The number of active tasks on the environment per task execution status which can be either Active or On hold. > The number of testers that are attached to the environment. > The number of tasks executed on an environment over last month per execution status.


/environment/{envId}/summary/{interval}

environmentEnvIdTaskCountGet

Gets the number of TDM tasks of the target Environment. If an Environment is connected to TDM tasks, a warning messahe is given to the user if the user deletes the Environment.


/environment/{envId}/taskCount

environmentEnvIdValidateListPost

Adds an Exclusion List to the TDM environment.The Exclusion List is being validated. If at least of the the entites is already included in another Exclusion List of the Environment and the Business Entity, the API returns this list and the user is asked to change ther entities in the Exclusion List.


/environment/{envId}/validateList

environmentEnvIdValidateRequestedByPost

Checks if an exclusion list already exists for the user, environment and business entity. If yes- a new list cannot be opened. Insrtead, the existing list can be updated.


/environment/{envId}/validateRequestedBy

environmentGetAllGlobalsGet

Gets the list of all Global variables defined in the Fabric project except the TDM product Globals. If the optional input "lus" parameter is populated, return only shared Globals or Globals defined in the input LUs.


/environment/getAllGlobals

environmentPost

Creates a new Environment. The following parameters are mandatory: environment_name, allow_write, and allow_read. Notes: > Both parameters - environment_name and fabric environment_name - are populated by one of the Fabric's environments. > The sync_mode parameter can be populated by one of the following values: "OFF", "FORCE", or null. > The allow_write parameter is set to true if the environment can be used as a target environment. Else, set this parameter to false. > The allow_read parameter is set to true if the environment can be used as a source environment. Else, set this parameter to false. Example of a request body: {"allow_write":true,"environment_name":"ENV6","environment_description":"test","owners":[{"uid":"king123","user_id":"king123","displayName":"king123","username":"king123"}]}


/environment

environmentsbyuserandbeGet

Get a list of environments that are available for the user and contain a system (product) that has the root Logical Unit of the input Business Entity (BE). This API is called when creating or editing a task to get the available environments for the user and the task's BE.


/environmentsbyuserandbe

listOfEnvsByUserGet

Gets the list of the user's TDM active environments and the role ID of each environment. - If the user's permission group is Admin: - Select all active environments and populate the role_id by "admin". - If the user's permission group is Owner, select the following environments: - Select all active environments where the user is set as environment owner. Populate the role_id by "owner". - Select all active environments where the user is attached to by a TDM environment role. Populate the role_id by the TDM environment's role_id. - If the user's permission group is "Tester": - Select all active environments where the user is attached to by a TDM environment role. Populate the role_id by the TDM Environment's role. Notes: - A TDM Environment's role can be attached to selected users or to all TDM users. A user can be attached to a TDM Environment role by their user id. - A user cannot be attached to multiple TDM environment role on a given environment. Therefore, if a user is attached to a TDM Environment role by their user id, the 'ALL' role is not applicable for this user.


/listOfEnvsByUser

wsAddPermissionGroupMappingPost

Adds a new mapping between a TDM Permission Group and a Fabric role. The relation of Fabric roles and TDM permission groups is many to one. i.e. each Fabric role can be mapped into one TDM Permission Group, but it is possible to map several Fabric roles into a given TDM Permission Group.


/wsAddPermissionGroupMapping

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python

 -H "Authorization: Bearer [[accessToken]]"\
-H "Accept: application/json,application/xml"\
-H "Content-Type: application/json"\
"http://localhost:3214/api/wsAddPermissionGroupMapping"

logicalunitswithoutproductGet

Gets a list of Logical Units (LUs) that are not attached to any TDM System (product) and available to be attached to the given TDM system. This API is called when attaching a combination of a Business Entity (BE) and an LU to a given TDM system.


/logicalunitswithoutproduct

productPost

Creates a TDM System (product). Notes: > The product_name and product_versions parameters are mandatory. > At least one version must be set for a product. Multiple product versions can also be set, seperaed by a comma. For example: "1.5,1.0,2.0". > Each Active product gets a unique product name.


/product

productProdIdPut

Updates the System's (product) description, vendor, or versions. The versions are separated by a comma. Example request body: { "product_name": "PROD", "product_description": "desc", "product_vendor": "verndor", "product_versions": "1.0,2.0" }


/product/{prodId}

TDMReserveEntities

addNotePost

Add a note to the input list of reserved entities. Each entity must have the following parameters: - "environment_name": the name of the environment where the entity is reserved, - "be_name": the name of the Business Entity of the entity ID, - "target_entity_id": the entity ID. Request BODY example: { "newNote": "Testing the entity reservation!", "listOfEntities": [ { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name":"Customer", "target_entity_id":"4984" }, { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name":"Customer", "target_entity_id":"480" } ] }


/addNote

extendPost

Update the reservation period of the input entity list: update the reservation's expiration date with the input date. If the user is added to the environment as a tester, the new end date cannot exceed the limitation of the testers reservation period defined in tdm_general_parameters TDM table. For example, if the maximum reservation period is 10 days and the entity has been reserved on 10-MAR-22, the maximum expiration date on this entity can be set to 20-MAR-22. Each entity must have the following parameters: - "environment_name": the name of the environment where the entity is reserved, - "be_name": the name of the Business Entity of the entity ID, - "target_entity_id": the entity ID. The newEndDate must be populated with the following format: 'YYYYMMDDHHMMSS'. Request BODY examples: { "newEndDate": "20220210000000", "listOfEntities": [ { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name": "BE", "target_entity_id": "3" } ] } { "newEndDate": "20220328235900", "listOfEntities": [{"environment_name":"TAR","be_name":"Customer","target_entity_id":"192"},{"environment_name":"TAR","be_name":"Customer","target_entity_id":"3097"}] }


/extend

releaseListOfEntitiesPost

Release the input entity list. The release activity deletes the entities from the TDM reservation table (TDM_RESERVED_ENTITIES). Each entity must have the following parameters: - "environment_name": the name of the environment where the entity is reserved, - "be_name": the name of the Business Entity of the entity ID, - "target_entity_id": the entity ID. Request BODY example: { "listOfEntities": [ { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name":"Customer", "target_entity_id":"4984" }, { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name":"Customer", "target_entity_id":"480" } ] }


/release/listOfEntities

validateReservedEntitiesListPost

Validate each input entity ID if it is reserved for another user in the input environment. If the entity is reserved for another user in the environment, return a failure on the entity. Request BODY example: { "beID": "1", "envID": "2", "listOfEntities": [ { "target_entity_id": "1" }, { "target_entity_id": "3" }, { "target_entity_id": "4" } ] }


/validateReservedEntitiesList

validatenoofreservedGet

A tester user can reserve a limited number of entities per Business Entity and environment. The maximum number of reserved entities is set in the Environment permission set attached to the user. Admin and environment owners can reserve an unlimited number of entities in the environment. The API performs the following validation if the user is not an admin user and is not the owner of the environment: Get the Write permission set attached to the user. If the user does not have a Write permission set in the environment, an exception is thrown by the API. Sum the input number of entities with the number of entities that are already reserved by the user in the environment (if they exist). Validate that the the total number of reserved entities does not exceed the user's permissions. Example: - The user can reserve up to 70 customers on ST1. - The user already has 40 customers reserved on ST1. - The user asks to reserve 35 entities in the task: 40+35 = 75. - The API returns an error since the user cannot exceed a total of 70 customers (40 + 30) in the task.


/validatenoofreserved

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl

validatereserveretentionperiodPost

Validate if the given retention period on the input entity list and environment does not exceed the max retention period allowed for user. An admin user of the environment's owner can set an unlimited retention period. If the entities are already reserved by the user, check the new expiration date against the existing start reservation date. Else, check the retention period against the current Datetime. The validated retention period can be populated either by the combination of retentionUnit and retentionValue input parameters or by populating the newEndDateTime parameter. If the retention unit and values are populated, validate the reservation period based on these parameter. Else, validate the reservation period based on the input newEndDateTime. Request BODY examples: Example 1: populate the retention unit and value parameters: { "retentionUnit": "Days", "retentionValue": 8, "listOfEntities": [ { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name": "Customer", "target_entity_id": "1" }, { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name": "Customer", "target_entity_id": "2" } ] } Example 2: populate the new newEndDateTime parameter: { "newEndDateTime": "20220218000000", "listOfEntities": [ { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name": "Customer", "target_entity_id": "1" }, { "environment_name": "TAR", "be_name": "Customer", "target_entity_id": "2" } ] }


/validatereserveretentionperiod

TDMTasks

businessentityBeIdEnvironmentEnvIdLogicalunitsGet

Gets the Logical Units list of the task's Business Entity (BE) and the task's environment products. The user can select part or all of the LUs in the list in the task. For extract task, the source environment ID is sent to the API, and for load task the target environment ID is sent to the API.


/businessentity/{beId}/environment/{envId}/logicalunits

businessentityBeIdSourceEnvSrcEnvNameAnalysiscountPost

Calculates the number of entities that matches the selected task's parameters. The calculation is based on the task's Business Entity (BE), source environment, and the Where statement (populated in the request Body) reflecting the selected parameters. Use the ANY command when checking a value of a parameter since the TDM LU parameter tables contain an array of values on each parameter. Example of a request body: { "tar_env_name": "TAR", "where": "(( 'Alise' = ANY(\"CUSTOMER.FIRST_NAME\") ))", "filterout_reserved": false }


/businessentity/{beId}/sourceEnv/{src_env_name}/analysiscount

checkMigrateStatusForEntitiesListPost

This API is invoked when creating a Data Flux load task to validate the selected version. It validates the entity list of the Data Flux load task and checks if all entities have been successfully migrated into Fabric by the selected version. Failed entities are marked with 'false' and successfully migrated entities are marked with 'true' indication. If some entities are marked with 'false', an error message is given to the user to update the load task and remove the failed entities from the entity list. Example of a request body: { "entitlesList": "1,2,7", "taskExecutionId": "38", "luList": "Customer, Billing, Orders" }


/checkMigrateStatusForEntitiesList

Usage and SDK Samples

environmentEnvIdBusinessEntitiesForEnvProductsGet

Gets the list of available Business Entities that can be selected in the task based on the related Products of the task's environment. The API checks the source environment of Extract tasks and the target environment of Load tasks.


/environment/{envId}/businessEntitiesForEnvProducts

extractrefstatsPost

Gets a summary or detailed information of the reference tables execution of a given task execution id. The type is the run mode of the API and can have the following values: > 'D': detailed execution. Returning a detailed information of all reference tables their execution status. > 'S': summary information of the execution


/extractrefstats

getDMPopParamsGet

Get the list of parameters of the given custom Flow. It gets a list of LU Names separated by comma, and optional task id. Task Id will be sent in case of updating an existing task, to get the values already set in that task.


/getDMPopParams

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python

 -H "Authorization: Bearer [[accessToken]]"\
-H "Accept: application/json,application/xml"\
"http://localhost:3214/api/getDMPopParams?luList=&taskId="
import io.swagger.client.*;
import io.swagger.client.auth.*;
import io.swagger.client.model.*;
import io.swagger.client.api.TDMTasksApi;

import java.io.File;
import java.util.*;

public class TDMTasksApiExample {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApiClient defaultClient = Configuration.getDefaultApiClient();


        TDMTasksApi apiInstance = new TDMTasksApi();
        String luList = luList_example; // String |

getEnvironmentsForTaskAttrGet

Get the list of environments that are aligned with the input filtering parameters, according to the task type and attributes, as follows: - If the task type is Extract , then validate and return the list of available source environments. - If the task type is Load, then validate and return both - source and target environments. - If the task type is Reserve (reserve only task), then validate and return the list of available target environments. - If the task is a delete only task, then validate and return the list of available target environments.


/getEnvironmentsForTaskAttr

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python

 -H "Authorization: Bearer [[accessToken]]"\
-H "Accept: application/json,application/xml"\

        TDMTasksApi apiInstance = new TDMTasksApi();
        String be = be_example; // String | Populated by the task's be_id (Business Entity ID). For example: 1.
        String lus = lus_example; // String | Populated by the task's Logical Units (LU IDs), separated by comma. Example : 1,5,6,7
        String taskType = taskType_example; // String | Populated by "extract", "load", or "reserve"
        Integer refcount = 56; // Integer | 
        String selectionMethod = selectionMethod_example; // String | Can be populated by the following values: "L" (entity list), "R" (random selection), "S" (entity cloning),  "C" (custom logic), "PR" (parameters with a random selection), "P" (parameters), "ALL" (all entities), or "REF" (reference only task)
        String syncMode = syncMode_example; // String | Can be populated by 'OFF', 'FORCE', or can be empty
        Boolean versionInd = true; // Boolean | 
        Boolean replaceSequences = true; // Boolean | 
        Boolean deleteBeforeLoad = true; // Boolean | 
        Boolean reserveInd = true; // Boolean | 
        try {
            Object result = apiInstance.getEnvironmentsForTaskAttrGet(be, lus, taskType, refcount, selectionMethod, syncMode, versionInd, replaceSequences, deleteBeforeLoad, reserveInd);
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            System.err.println("Exception when calling TDMTasksApi#getEnvironmentsForTaskAttrGet");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

getcustomlogicflowsGet

Get the list of custom logic flows to be used to select the list of entities for give root LU. The input can be one root LU or more separated by comma.


/getcustomlogicflows

Returns the list children LUs of a parent LU in a task execution. This API is invoked when navigating the Logical Units Hierarchy tab of a selected task execution.


/luChildren

migrateStatusWsPost

Gets a summary or detailed information of the input batch id (LU execution). This API gets the run mode and a list of batch IDs or only one batch id as input values. The run mode can have the following values: > 'D': detailed execution. Returns detailed information of all entities and their execution status. > 'S': summary information of the execution > 'H': get the batch command. Example of a request body: {"migrateIds" : ["387a3b82-18e2-4d45-9482-16dc6ad15385","387a3b82-18e2-4d45-9482-16dc6ad15386"], "runModes" : ["D", "H", "S"]}


/migrateStatusWs

taskGetReferenceTaskTablePost

Gets the list of available Reference tables for a task based on the task's Logical Units (LUs). Task type can be either LOAD or EXTRACT. Example of a request body: {"task_type":"LOAD","logicalUnits":["Customer","Orders"]}


/task/getReferenceTaskTable

taskRefsTableTaskIdGet

Gets the list of reference table included in a given task. Note that refcount attribute of /tasks API is populated by the number of Reference tables included in the task. If the refcount attribute is populated by zero, the task does not have Reference tables.


/task/refsTable/{task_id}

taskStatsPost

Gets task execution details: > List of copied and Failed Entities. > Task's Logical Units hierarchy tree. > List of copied and failed reference tables. Examples of a request body: > Get the execution details of the root Logical Unit: {taskExecutionId: "69"} > Get the execution details of a selected Logical Unit: {taskExecutionId: "69", lu_name: "PATIENT_VISITS"} > Gets the execution details of a selected Logical Unit and entity ID: {taskExecutionId: "69", targetId: "400", lu_name: "PATIENT_VISITS"}

taskTaskIdForcedForcedStartTaskPost

Starts an execution of a TDM task. A task execution can override the following parameters: - entitieslist: populated by a list of entities separated by a comma. Note that the entity list can only contain one entity ID when executing a task with an Entity Clone selection method. - sourceEnvironmentName: source environment name. - targetEnvironmentName: target environment name. - taskGlobals: list of Global variables and their values. - numberOfEntities: populated by a number to change the number of entities processed by the task. This parameter is only relevant for Load tasks when the entitylist override parameter is not set. - dataVersionExecId: populated with the task execution id of the selected data version. The parameter can be set on Data Versioning load tasks. - dataVersionRetentionPeriod: populated with the retention period of the extracted data version. This parameter contains the unit (Hours, Days, Weeks?) and the value. - reserveInd: populated with true or false. Set to true if the task execution needs to reserve the entities on the target environment. - reserveRetention: populated with the reservation period of the task's entities. This parameter contains the unit (Hours, Days, Weeks.) and the value. - executionNote: Free text. Add a note to the execution. The task execution is validated whether the execution parameters are overridden or taken from the task itself: - Do not enable an execution if the TDM task execution processes are down. - Test the connection details of the source and target environments of the task execution if the forced parameter is false. - Do not enable an execution if another execution with the same execution parameters is already running on the task. - Validate the task's BE and LUs with the TDM products of the task execution's source and target environment. - Verify that the user is permitted to execute the task on the task execution's source and target environment. For example, the user cannot run a Load task with a sequence replacement on environment X if the user does not have permissions to run such a task on this environment. - Validate a Data Versioning extract task: verify that the given retention period do not exceed the maximum retention allowed for the user. Entity Reservation Validations: =========================== - Validate the number of reserved entities: if the task reserves the entities whether the reserve_ind is set to true in the task itself or in the overridden parameters, accumulate the number of entities in the task to the total number of reserved entities for the user on the target environment. If the total number of reserved entities exceeds the user's permissions on the environment, return an error. For example, if the user is allowed to reserved up to 70 entities in ST1 and there are 50 entities that are already reserved for the user in ST1, the user can reserve up to 20 additional entities in ST1. - Validate the retention period to verify that the number of days does not exceed the maximum number of days allowed for the tester. If at least one of the validations fail, the API does not start the task. Instead it returns a FAILED status and populates the list of validation errors in the results. Below is the list of the validation codes, returned by the API: - BEandLUs - Reference - selectionMethod - Versioning - ReplaceSequence - DeleteBeforeLoad - syncMode - totalNumberOfReservedEntities - versioningRetentionPeriod - reserveRetentionPeriod If the validations pass successfully, start the task execution. Note that if a Global's value is a JSON, it is required to add backslash to the values. See example. Request body example: { "entitieslist": "1,2,4,9,8,11", "sourceEnvironmentName": "SRC", "targetEnvironmentName": "TAR", "taskGlobals": { "CUST_TYPE": "BUS", "Customer.SUB_TYPE": "XX" }, "numberOfEntities": 14, "dataVersionExecId": 2, "dataVersionRetentionPeriod": { "unit": "Days", "value": "10" }, "reserveInd": true, "reserveRetention": { "unit": "Days", "value": "5" }, "executionNote": "Example Task" }


/task/{taskId}/forced/{forced}/startTask

taskTaskIdGlobalsGet

This API gets the task's Globals if they exist. Note that task_globals attribute of /tasks API indicates if the task has globals. This attribute is populated by true if the task has Globals.


/task/{taskId}/globals

tasksGet

This is the main API to get the task details. This API gets the list of all TDM tasks or a list of given task IDs if the input task_ids parameter is populated. The input task_ids is an optional parameter that can be populated to return the data of a given list of tasks. The ID(s) of the required task(s), will be supplied in this parameter separated by comma. For example, task_ids=4 or task_ids=3,2,6. If task_ids parameter is not populated, the data of all tasks will be returned by the API.


/tasks

tasksValidateVersionForLoadPost

Checks if the list of requested entities are copied successfully in the selected data version across all the input LU names in the task'sBusiness Entity hierarchy (the versionsForLoad API only checks the status of root LUI). For example, if the customer's order is not extracted succesfuly to Fabric, the validation on the related customer returns it as a failed entity. Example of a request body: { "entitiesList": "1,2", "taskExecId": "2", "lu_list": [ { "lu_name": "Billing" }, { "lu_name": "Customer" }, { "lu_name": "Orders" } ] }


/tasks/validateVersionForLoad

tasksVersionsForLoadPost

Get the list of the available data versions that match the input parameters. The user can select one of the data versions for the Data Versioning load task and reload the entities in the selected versions to the target environment. The API filters our expired data versions. For example, a data version that is created with a retention period of 5 days, will no longer be able to be retrieved after 6 days have passed. Note that the from date and to date inputs must be populated with "MM.DD.YYYY" or "MM-DD-YYYYY" date formats. Request BODY examples: { "fromDate":"2022-02-18", "toDate":"2022-03-21", "entitiesList":"", "lu_list":[ {"lu_name":"Customer"}, {"lu_name":"Billing"}, {"lu_name":"Orders"}, {"lu_name":"Collection"}], "source_env_name":"TAR", "target_env_name":"TAR","be_id":1 } { "fromDate":"2022-02-18", "toDate":"2022-03-21", "entitiesList":"1, 2", "lu_list":[ {"lu_name":"Customer"}, {"lu_name":"Billing"}, {"lu_name":"Orders"}, {"lu_name":"Collection"}], "source_env_name":"TAR", "target_env_name":"TAR","be_id":1 }


/tasks/versionsForLoad

wsTaskMonitorTaskIDGet

Returns the details of the input task execution ID if populated. When the task execution id is empty, the API returns current/last execution of the given task id. If the latest task execution is pending, it will only return its status, else it will return the statistics of the entities handled by the task execution.


/wsTaskMonitor/{taskID}

Usage and SDK Samples

  • Curl
  • Java
  • Android
  • Obj-C
  • JavaScript
  • C#
  • PHP
  • Perl
  • Python

 -H "Authorization: Bearer [[accessToken]]"\
-H "Accept: application/json,application/xml"\
"http://localhost:3214/api/wsTaskMonitor/{taskID}?executionID="
